    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This is a common point of confusion with loan amortization, and it's usually because of how interest accrues. In the early stages of a loan, the majority of your fixed monthly payment goes toward covering the interest charged on the outstanding principal balance. Only a smaller portion is actually chipping away at the principal itself. As time goes on, the interest amount decreases, allowing a larger chunk of your payment to go toward the principal, which is why the balance eventually starts to drop faster.",
