    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh i see. so it's basically because the interest is calculated on the total amount I still owe? can you explain the math a bit more? like if i have a $30k loan at 6% interest, how much of my first payment is actually going to interest vs principal?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's exactly right; interest is calculated on the remaining principal balance. For a $30,000 loan at 6% APR, the monthly interest charge is calculated by taking the annual rate (0.06) divided by 12 (0.005) and multiplying it by the principal ($30,000). This results in a monthly interest cost of $150. If your monthly payment is, say, $550, then $150 goes to interest, leaving $400 to reduce the principal.",
      "source": "target",
