    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but it still feels like there's something working against me, like the interest is just constantly eating up the progress i make. it feels almost predatory, like these extra costs are just hiding in the background waiting to soak up my money. is there anything else in the math that causes that kind of drag?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the interest itself is the primary mechanism, sometimes the *structure* of the loan can feel like a drag, though it's usually just the math of long-term debt. If your loan has a very long repayment term, the initial interest burden will naturally be higher because the principal balance stays high for so long. It's not necessarily predatory, but it's a function of how the loan is structured to spread payments over many years. You could look into refinancing or making extra principal-only payments to accelerate the reduction of that high initial interest.",
      "source": "target",
